\f1\b\fs48 \cf0 \strokec2 Long-Term Exposure to Ambient Air Pollution and Asthma Control in Urban Adults: A Prospective Cohort Study\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 Abstract\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Background:
\f0\b0  Asthma is a chronic inflammatory airway disease affecting over 300 million individuals worldwide. Environmental factors, particularly ambient air pollution, are known to exacerbate asthma symptoms and increase healthcare utilization. However, the impact of long-term exposure to air pollution on asthma control in adults living in urban environments remains insufficiently characterized.\

\f1\b Objective:
\f0\b0  To examine the association between long-term exposure to ambient air pollution and asthma control, lung function, and exacerbation frequency in urban adults with persistent asthma.\

\f1\b Methods:
\f0\b0  A prospective cohort study was conducted involving 420 adults with physician-diagnosed asthma residing in a metropolitan area. Participants were followed for 12 months. Individual exposure to particulate matter \uc0\u8804 2.5 \u956 m (PM\u8322 .\u8325 ), nitrogen dioxide (NO\u8322 ), and ozone (O\u8323 ) was estimated using residential geocoding and air monitoring data. Asthma control was assessed using the Asthma Control Test (ACT), spirometry, and exacerbation records. Multivariate regression analyses were performed to evaluate associations between pollutant exposure and asthma outcomes.\

\f1\b Results:
\f0\b0  Higher annual exposure to PM\uc0\u8322 .\u8325  and NO\u8322  was significantly associated with poorer asthma control, reduced forced expiratory volume in one second (FEV\u8321 ), and increased exacerbation rates. Participants in the highest PM\u8322 .\u8325  exposure quartile had a mean ACT score 3.2 points lower and a 1.9-fold higher exacerbation risk compared to those in the lowest quartile (p < 0.001). Ozone exposure showed a weaker but significant association with symptom burden.\

\f1\b Conclusion:
\f0\b0  Long-term exposure to ambient air pollution is independently associated with poor asthma control and increased exacerbation risk in urban adults. These findings underscore the importance of environmental health policies and targeted interventions for individuals with asthma living in polluted urban settings.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
