\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Introduction\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Asthma is a heterogeneous chronic respiratory disease characterized by airway inflammation, bronchial hyperresponsiveness, and variable airflow obstruction. Despite advances in pharmacological therapy and disease management strategies, many patients continue to experience poor symptom control and frequent exacerbations. Environmental exposures play a critical role in asthma pathophysiology and disease expression, particularly in urban populations.\
Air pollution is a major global public health concern, contributing to millions of premature deaths annually. Urban environments are characterized by elevated levels of traffic-related pollutants, including particulate matter, nitrogen oxides, and ozone. These pollutants have been linked to adverse respiratory outcomes, including asthma development, symptom exacerbation, and reduced lung function.\
Short-term exposure to air pollution is well established as a trigger for asthma exacerbations. However, the effects of chronic, long-term exposure on asthma control and disease progression are less clearly defined, particularly in adult populations. Most existing studies have focused on pediatric cohorts or acute exposure events, limiting the understanding of sustained environmental impacts on adult asthma.\
Long-term exposure to air pollutants may perpetuate airway inflammation, promote structural airway changes, and reduce responsiveness to inhaled corticosteroids. Understanding these associations is essential for informing both clinical management and public health interventions aimed at improving asthma outcomes.\
This study aimed to investigate the relationship between long-term ambient air pollution exposure and asthma control, lung function, and exacerbation frequency in adults residing in an urban environment.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Methods\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 Study Design and Ethics\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 This was a prospective cohort study conducted between January 2023 and January 2024. The study protocol was approved by the institutional ethics review board, and all participants provided written informed consent prior to enrollment.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Participants\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Adults aged 18\'9665 years with physician-diagnosed persistent asthma were recruited from outpatient pulmonary clinics across a large metropolitan area. Inclusion criteria included asthma diagnosis for at least one year, use of controller medication, and residence at the same address for a minimum of two years. Exclusion criteria included smoking history exceeding 10 pack-years, diagnosis of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, pregnancy, and significant cardiopulmonary comorbidities.\
A total of 420 participants met eligibility criteria and were enrolled.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Exposure Assessment\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Long-term exposure to air pollution was estimated using residential address geocoding and data from fixed-site air quality monitoring stations. Annual average concentrations of PM\uc0\u8322 .\u8325 , NO\u8322 , and O\u8323  were calculated for each participant based on proximity-weighted monitoring data. Exposure levels were categorized into quartiles for analysis.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Outcome Measures\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Asthma Control\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 Asthma control was assessed using the validated Asthma Control Test (ACT), with scores ranging from 5 to 25. An ACT score below 20 indicated uncontrolled asthma.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Lung Function\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 Spirometry was performed at baseline and 12 months according to standardized guidelines. Forced expiratory volume in one second (FEV\uc0\u8321 ) and forced vital capacity (FVC) were recorded as percentages of predicted values.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa319\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Asthma Exacerbations\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 Exacerbations were defined as episodes requiring systemic corticosteroids, emergency department visits, or hospitalization. Exacerbation frequency was recorded through medical records and participant interviews.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Covariates\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Data were collected on age, sex, body mass index (BMI), socioeconomic status, medication adherence, physical activity, indoor allergen exposure, and comorbid allergic rhinitis. These variables were included as potential confounders in statistical analyses.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Statistical Analysis\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Continuous variables were expressed as mean \'b1 standard deviation, and categorical variables as percentages. Multivariate linear and Poisson regression models were used to assess associations between pollutant exposure and asthma outcomes, adjusting for covariates. A p-value < 0.05 was considered statistically significant.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
