\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Results\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 Participant Characteristics\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Of the 420 participants, 401 completed the 12-month follow-up. The mean age was 42.7 \'b1 11.3 years, and 58% were female. Baseline asthma severity, medication use, and lung function were similar across exposure quartiles.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Air Pollution Exposure\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Mean annual concentrations were 18.6 \uc0\u956 g/m\'b3 for PM\u8322 .\u8325 , 32.4 ppb for NO\u8322 , and 41.2 ppb for O\u8323 . Participants in higher exposure quartiles were more likely to reside near major roadways and in areas of lower socioeconomic status.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Asthma Control\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Higher exposure to PM\uc0\u8322 .\u8325  and NO\u8322  was significantly associated with lower ACT scores. Participants in the highest PM\u8322 .\u8325  quartile had a mean ACT score of 17.1 \'b1 3.4 compared to 20.3 \'b1 3.1 in the lowest quartile (p < 0.001). Similar trends were observed for NO\u8322  exposure.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Lung Function\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 FEV\uc0\u8321  percent predicted was significantly lower among participants with higher PM\u8322 .\u8325  exposure. After adjustment, each 5 \u956 g/m\'b3 increase in PM\u8322 .\u8325  was associated with a 3.6% reduction in FEV\u8321  (p = 0.002). No significant association was observed between O\u8323  exposure and lung function decline.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Asthma Exacerbations\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Participants in the highest PM\uc0\u8322 .\u8325  exposure quartile experienced a higher annual exacerbation rate compared to those in the lowest quartile (1.8 vs. 0.9 exacerbations per year; incidence rate ratio 1.9, p < 0.001). NO\u8322  exposure showed a similar but slightly weaker association.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
