\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Discussion\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 This prospective cohort study demonstrates that long-term exposure to ambient air pollution, particularly PM\uc0\u8322 .\u8325  and NO\u8322 , is independently associated with poor asthma control, reduced lung function, and increased exacerbation frequency in urban adults. These findings highlight the chronic impact of environmental pollutants on asthma beyond acute symptom triggering.\
The observed association between PM\uc0\u8322 .\u8325  exposure and reduced lung function may reflect persistent airway inflammation and oxidative stress induced by fine particulate matter. Traffic-related pollutants such as NO\u8322  may further contribute to airway hyperresponsiveness and diminished response to controller medications.\
The weaker association observed with ozone exposure may be due to its seasonal variability and greater relevance to acute rather than chronic respiratory effects. Nonetheless, ozone remains an important contributor to symptom burden in susceptible individuals.\
Strengths of this study include its prospective design, comprehensive exposure assessment, and adjustment for multiple confounding variables. Limitations include potential exposure misclassification and lack of personal air monitoring data. Additionally, the study population was limited to urban residents, which may limit generalizability to rural settings.\
Future research should explore interventions aimed at reducing personal exposure to air pollution, such as air filtration systems and urban planning strategies, and evaluate their impact on asthma outcomes.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf3 \strokec3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 Conclusion\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Long-term exposure to ambient air pollution is associated with poorer asthma control, reduced lung function, and increased exacerbation risk in urban adults with asthma. These findings emphasize the importance of addressing environmental determinants of health in asthma management and support the need for public health policies aimed at improving urban air quality.\
